File: brew.info, Node: Using menus, Next: Context documentation, Prev: Some brew basics, Up: Users manual

Using menus
===========

Brew has it's own form of user interface. It is a kind of active text.

Usually this text menus serve the purpose of giving informations about
current settings and give an interface to change them.

You can select things on the screen by moving the cursor on it and
pressing `RET'. If you select the menu title or press `?' you can read
the documentation about the menu.

Most menus also have key bindings, which are more convenient once you
get used to them. (*Note Key bindings::). Press `k' for key bindings.

To leave a menu press `q'.
As menus do nest, this will usually bring you back to the prior menu.
(Pressing `q' repeatedly will always bring you back to brews main screen).

`?' gives context sensitive documentation.


Many brew menus have some built in 'intelligence'. Don't be surprised
if things appear or disappear depending on your selections. Brew tries
to present you only the information and selection possibilities
relevant to a given situation. Sometimes menus give hints or warnings,
or even reset your input (if you try to set something to an impossible
value).

* Menu:

* Menu example::                How a menu might look.
* Moving and selecting::        How to select menu items.
* Key bindings::                Key bindings and how to find them out.
* Colours in menus::            
* Numeric input::               Hidden capabilities when entering numbers.
* Float input::                 Everyday float syntax on input.
* Scale input::                 Input of fractions.
* Selecting functions::         Selecting functions from a list.
* Scrolling menus::             When menus do not fit on a screen.
* Using Forth in menus::        Using the whole power of Forth in menus.




File: brew.info, Node: Menu example, Next: Moving and selecting, Prev: Using menus, Up: Using menus

