File: brew.info, Node: Individuals menu, Next: Nuc menu, Prev: Menus menu, Up: Users manual

Individuals menu
================

You reach the individuals menu by pressing `I' from brews main screen.
This menu lets you select from a list of predefined individuals.

You can edit the selected individual as you wish and set it somewhere
in your brew universe. This menu has it's main function when you set
up a new evolution. You can add new individuals to a biotope later on
of course, if you decide to do so. (You might be surprised how
difficult it is to do so successfully, when the other cells are
already somehow optimised to the given conditions though).

Press `i' to select an individual from the list.
Press `e' to examine and edit it as you like.

If you return to the main screen now you can set clones of this
individual by pressing `<RET>' on a spot. Brew displays `Clone nuc by
selecting an empty spot' at the bottom line to let you know. You could
edit each clone again, of course. This possibility is lost as soon
brew gets confused which individual you might mean. Just select and
edit it again to continue then.

If you want to randomly sow a number of clones use the function
presented in the menu (`c'). There is a variant which diversifies
diversificable nuc variables of each sown clone (`d'), making them a
bit different, which is usually a good idea to start an evolution.
*Note Diversification menu::, to configure variable diversification.

Please note that brew does try but not *insist* to sow as many cells
as you tell it to. If a cell falls on a spot that is already occupied
it will be lost, like a seed falling on infertile ground.

Of course you can select a first individual, set or sow it, select
another one (or edit it differently) and set some more if you want to
start with more than one species. Don't forget to make them look
different so you can *see* what's happening with them.




File: brew.info, Node: Nuc menu, Next: Edit spot menu, Prev: Individuals menu, Up: Users manual

Nuc menu
========

This menu screen gives you detailed information about a individual cell
and let's you edit it. You reach this menu by selecting a nuc in brews
world map (world display) or from individuals menu. Editing a nuc changes
only this single cell of course.

Most of the menu items refer to variables local to the nuc. Brew let's
you edit all of them (with very few exceptions), even if it thinks
it's a bad idea. Changing some variables like the ID of the cell could
confuse brew. So brew warns you by ringing the bell when you try to do
so, but does not prevent you from doing it (except in some really
dangerous cases).

Going through the menu from top to bottom:

   * `wake-me'. This is the cells genome. It get's executed when the
     cell is woken up. Look at the definition of the code by selecting
     it's name (*Note Selecting functions::). This code get's mutated
     by the mutation process. Normally you will probably start a
     evolution with `noop'.

   * `<name>'. The genomes name or the information that this genome is
     on trial. Selecting it will let you examine or edit the genome.
     (*Note Gene edit menu::).

   * `.gene-info'. Gives you some information about the cells genome.

   * `select'. Selecting a cell just sets a certain flag in it's data.
     The flag is hereditary. You can use the flag to mark a cell to
     look at it's offspring. You can also mark groups of cells (from
     other menus) and do something with all selected cells, or just
     display them coloured. *Note Menu select nucs::, for more
     information.

   * `eat'. 'Eating' in brew mens getting energy. The eat function is
     the place where scoring takes place. It's a bit like animal
     training: Individuals that behave 'better' get more food. The
     cells can not see or change this function, only you can.

   * `score'. Raw scoring result without code taxes.

   * `reproduce'. Select the way the cell reproduces. Currently only
     `cell-division' is implemented, so you don't have much choice....

   * `show-me'. Select a function determining how the cell will show
     up in the world map. *Note Show me functions::, to see what is
     available.

   * `nuc id'. Each nuc has a unique identification number. It helps
     identifying it in log files. Normally it is not a good idea to
     change it.

   * `genome id'. Each genome has it's unique identification number.
     It helps identifying it in log files. Normally it is not a good
     idea to change it.

   * `code cost'. The longer the gene code, the higher the code cost.
     You can edit this value, but it will be recalculated by the
     mutation process as soon as the genome gets mutated next time.
     Your value has no longer any influence on the mutated genomes
     code cost then.

   * `nuc length'. Length of the nucs data structure. You cannot
     change this here.

   * `age'. The age of the cell in time steps. You can edit it if you
     want to cheat for some reason.

   * `age limit'. A nuc will die at the latest when he will get older
     than this maximal possible age.

   * `generation'. The cells generation since start of this evolution.

   * `genome gen'. Generation of this genome since last mutation.

   * `energy'. Amount of 'energy' the cell has available. A cell dies
     if it has no energy left and can reproduce if it's energy level
     surpasses `reproduction energy'. Energy is received through
     `eating' which will give more or less energy depending on how
     well the cell has solved it's task and on how much food there is.
     Each live step costs energy and gene code length does too. These
     values are used for `population control'. A mother cell passes
     it's energy on to the children, equally dividing it to give each
     one it's share.

   * `char'. If you set `show me' to `show-ascii' this char will be
     shown to symbolise the cell in spot display. Otherwise it has no
     influence at all.

   * `reproduction energy'. Energy level a cell must reach to be able
     to reproduce. Some other conditions (depending on `world mode' or
     `linear mode' respectively) must fit for successful reproduction.
     Energy is divided equally among the children. Nuc variables can
     get diversified and the genome can get mutated when a cell
     reproduces.

   * `Integer/Floating point Nuc variables'. The following screen area
     is dedicated to the nuc variables of all the different classes.
     Switch between INTEGER or FLOAT variable display (use `o', like
     usual). In the case of floats the menu further let's you choose
     between VISIBLE (to mutation) or HIDDEN variables (Please read
     *Note Variable names::).

     The number of nuc variables of each kind is configured at compile
     time. If there are more than fit on the screen the area where
     they are displayed will be scrolling (*Note Scrolling menus::).

   * `diversification'. Organs, parameters and invisibles can get
     diversified. There are two bitmasks to switch that on or off for
     each individual variable: a global one and a nuc individual one.
     A variable can only get diversified if both masks are on for it.
     Here you set the mask `my-diversifctn-mask' local to this nuc
     only. You will see the letter indices for each variable class.
     Lower case letters mean diversification is off, upper case means
     on. Brew lets you switch diversibility of the variables you have
     chosen above to be displayed. Please note that the mutation
     process automatically sets all the bits of this mask (but not of
     the global one) of which the variables in question get used by
     the genome. Mutation does not reset these bits, if the variables
     are not used any more. This is not a bug, it's part of the play.

   * `sow' and `sow diversified' work like from individuals menu
     (*Note Individuals menu::).

   * `remove cell' takes this cell out of the play.

   * `SPOT' let's you examine and edit the spot the nuc is on.




File: brew.info, Node: Edit spot menu, Next: Menu global variables, Prev: Nuc menu, Up: Users manual

Edit a single spot
==================

You will not want to examine or edit a single spot too frequently,
but here is a menu to do it anyway.

You reach this menu from brews main screen by pressing `l' on an empty
spot. (Pressing `<RET>' will have the same effect most of the time).
If the spot is occupied by a cell you can get here from the nuc menu
by selecting `Spot' therein.

You can see and edit either the different INTEGER or FLOAT spot
variables.

*Note Variable names::, for information about the different variable classes.
*Note Numeric input::, how to use Forth power in input.
*Note Float input::, let's you use everydays float syntax on input.
*Note Scrolling menus::, scrolling menus.




File: brew.info, Node: Menu global variables, Next: Food menu, Prev: Edit spot menu, Up: Users manual

Global variables
================

This menu let's you see and edit global integer or float variables.
You get here from brews main screen by pressing `V'.

These variables are the simplest type of environment variables.
Normally you will give the genome read only access to them,
if you use them at all.

You can see and edit either the different INTEGER or FLOAT global
variables. Key `o' toggles as usual.

To set them all to the same value, set the first one and select
`set them all to this value'.

To configure diversification of global variables use the link to
*Note Diversification menu::.

*Note Numeric input::, how to use Forth power in input.
*Note Float input::, to use everydays float syntax on input.
*Note Scrolling menus::, scrolling menus.




File: brew.info, Node: Food menu, Next: Population control, Prev: Menu global variables, Up: Users manual

Food menu
=========

The cells need `energy' to survive and to reproduce.
They get energy by `eating' `food'.

Population get's controlled by two means:
   * Limiting food supply.
   * Adapting `energy costs' for each life step and for code length.

This menu is for food supply configuration.
You get here by pressing `F' in brew main screen.


Food portions are given once a evolutionary time step.
There are different ways to distribute food:

   * `World food supply'. This food amount is equally divided and
     shared amongst all living cells. It is a good help to control
     population size. But if you depend too much on it population size
     will oscillate very much, which might be problematic.

   * `Individual food share'. Each living individual get's this much
     food extra. This works against stabilising population.

   * `Food share on spot'. Food is deposed on spots where it remains
     until a cell eats it up there. Food accumulation on empty spots
     leads to moving cell cultures. Apart from a more interesting look
     in world view this has a stabilising effect on population size
     and influences the development of evolution. Food deposits on
     empty spots postpone the effect of population control measures,
     which stabilises oscillations to some degree. The influence on
     the course of evolution is complex.

   * `Feed world manually'. Sometimes you want to give a extra food
     portion to all spots and all cells.

   * Food menu let's you access some other functions you are likely to
     use to choose useful input, like scanning all spots and all nucs
     or configuring costs. These are just duplicate interfaces to
     functions explained elsewhere.




File: brew.info, Node: Population control, Next: Diversification menu, Prev: Food menu, Up: Users manual

Population control
==================

Evolution only will lead to useful results if there is some sort of
life stress that controls which genomes will survive and which will
not.

This menu let's you configure population control. You get here by
pressing `P' in brews main screen.

This brew version has two different ways of doing it:

* Menu:

* Eat and consume::             Get paid by results, pay taxes, consume energy.
* Elitism::                     Only the best individuals will survive.
* Menu elite::                  Current score list of the individuals.



File: brew.info, Node: Eat and consume, Next: Elitism, Prev: Population control, Up: Population control

Brews pseudo biological mode
----------------------------

Brew stresses it's little 'beings' by two means:
   * Limiting food supply.
   * Adapting `energy costs' for each life step and for code length.

This menu is for configuration of automatic adaption of energy costs.
It's a mean automatic stress producer!

Separing costs for gene code length and life steps gives you a
convenient way of controlling length of generated code.

Population control menu also deals with population emergencies.


Let me explain some technical terms first:

   * `High water mark', `Low water mark'. If population crosses these
     limits brew will automatically increase or decrease life stress
     in order to stabilise population in between them.

   * `Stress additive step'. Stress amount added (or subtracted) to
     the current stress when population is out of bounds.

   * `Stress rate'. Rate the current stress is multiplied (or divided)
     by when population is out of bounds.

   * `Population flood'. Population has crossed a critical limit. Brew
     takes drastical measures to decrease it.

   * `S.O.S.'. Population has fallen below a critical limit. Brew
     takes a number of drastical measures to save the population from
     dying out.


Configurating possibilities:

   * `Live stress, additive step'. Amount of additive live stress
     change when population is out of bounds.

   * `Stress rate'. Multiplicative live stress change when population
     is out of bounds (*Note Scale input::).

   * `Code price, additive step'. Amount of additive stress adaption
     (dependent on code length) when population is out of bounds.

   * `Code price rate'. Multiplicative stress change (dependent on
     code length) when population is out of bounds (*Note Scale
     input::).

   * `High water mark'. Beyond this limit brew will increase stress to
     keep population down.

   * `Flood-mark'.
     Beyond this limit brew will take drastic measures to cut population down.
     Brew will issue a message to you if that happens.

   * `Flood stress rate'. Multiplicative stress rate applied in case
     of population flood emergency (*Note Scale input::).

   * `Flood energy rate'. In case of population flood emergency the
     energy level of each living cell will get multiplied by this rate
     (*Note Scale input::).

   * `Flood food rate'. In case of population flood emergency
     population control will multiply all food rations (world food
     supply, individual food share, share on spot) by this ratio.
     (*Note Food menu::, *Note Scale input::). This measure should
     have a lasting effect on population size.

   * `Flood kill rate'. As a measure to have a immediate effect brew
     can remove a certain ratio of all living cells on population
     flood emergencies. This does not remedy the problem of course.
     (*Note Scale input::).

   * `Low water mark'. Whenever population falls below this level brew
     will automatically decrease stress to let the population grow
     again.

   * `Low water mark is active after step'. If you start an
     evolutionary experiment you are very likely to start with very
     few individuals, very often only a single one. You would not want
     brew to think this to be a population deficiency or population
     emergency. So population upwards regulation is set on hold for a
     number of time steps in the beginning. This also tries to force
     you to set up your experiment with somehow useful defaults, such
     that it can survive the start of the evolution without the help
     of population control. You would hardly get useful results out of
     a setup that wouldn't be able to start on one's own. Setting an
     experiment up in such a way is admittedly not always trivial. You
     might have to try out a bit, but it's worth the effort.

   * `Additive release'. Up regulation of population is done more
     rigidly than down regulation trying to avoid population
     breakdowns. This is the *factor* applied to additive stress
     change (applied as stress release, of course). Additive stress
     release will apply whenever population is less then the low water
     mark.

   * `Multiplicative release'. This is the *factor* by which
     multiplicative population regulation is stronger when applied
     upwards than downwards. (See last entry).

   * `SOS mark'. If population falls below this mark brew gets very
     alarmed and will apply very drastic measures to prevent the
     population from dying out completely. Brew will issue a message
     to you if it happens. Try to set up your experiments in a way it
     does not happen.

   * `SOS release rate'. In case of population breakdown emergency
     brew will apply this multiplicative rate to release both live
     stress and stress depending on gene code size. The additive
     stress steps also get adapted to the new situation depending on
     this rate (*Note Scale input::).

   * `Reproduction energy'. To push reproduction (on population
     breakdown emergency) brew will add the energy amount needed for
     reproduction multiplied by this factor to each living cells
     energy supply. This is emergency help only, not really solving
     the problem.

   * `SOS sow'. To have an immediate effect as emergency help on
     population breakdowns brew can sow clones for each living cell.
     This value determines the number of clones that will be spread
     over the world for each living individual.

   * `Current energy cost of each life step'. Current result of the
     above regulation process. Of course you can edit it by hand, but
     population control will continue to change it on his own behalf.
     It will start with your value at least.

   * `Can this 'cost' become a source of help in emergency
     situations?' When this is switched on, the stress can become
     negative. This can help in emergency situations. It can produce
     strange results sometimes, like genomes growing enormously when
     rating negative on gene code length. This does not happen too
     often, though.

   * `Current energy cost of code usage'. Current result of the above
     regulation process regarding gene code length regulation.

   * `rating scale'. Fixed scale not touched by population control to
     configure the weight of gene code length on applied stress (*Note
     Scale input::). If this rate is zero, code length will have no
     influence at all on applied stress. You can even set it negative
     for a short time, to let genomes grow. Then you carefully reset
     it to a small positive value and let mutation cut out all the
     useless code fragments. This can help mutation sometimes to find
     new survival tricks ;-)

   * `Scoring rate'. This is a third possibility to regulate
     population and to influence the course of the evolutionary
     process. Newer eating functions do their scoring more or less
     strictly depending this rate. So you set it large to start with,
     giving mutation a chance to try out ineffective gene code,
     setting it harder, when mutation *has* produced helpful code. You
     have to regulate this by hand, as population control does not use
     it automatically (yet?). Please note that not all eating
     functions do use it at all. (*Note Scale input::).

   * `Food supply'. As food supply is the other tool to regulate
     population you will find a link here. *Note Food menu::.





File: brew.info, Node: Elitism, Next: Menu elite, Prev: Eat and consume, Up: Population control

Elitism: only the best will survive
-----------------------------------

This more traditional way of population control works much more simple
and much more drastic: The cells get scored after each life step. Only
a fixed number of the fittest of them are kept, the others removed.
Population is filled up with mutated variations of the elite. Cells
are potentially immortal if they manage to stay in the elite.

   * `Population size'. This mechanism of population control tries to
     keep population at a fixed size. Note, that the actual population
     will often be smaller, because not all cells might have found a
     free spot for their offspring.

   * `Kept elite'. Number of the fittest individuals kept in the
     population. They will get used as base for mutations to fill up
     population to the desired size.

   * `Code price scale'. Scale for the gene code length to go into the
     scoring function.




