File: brew.info, Node: Diversification menu, Next: Mutation menu, Prev: Population control, Up: Users manual

Diversification menu
====================

The trick of evolutionary programming is to let the 'children' of a
code snippet you want to optimise be variations rather then exact
copies of the original. This is not only true for gene code, which
would be changed through `mutation', but also for nuc intern
(hereditary) variables, which are varied by `diversification'.

Later on I have found the diversification mechanism useful not only to
optimise inner variable values, but also to set up *input* for some
experiments. So I extended the possibilities of diversification on
spot variables too.

Sometimes it's unnecessary complicated to have these input variables
as local variables (to the spot or nuc), so I introduced a set of
global variables, which can get diversified too, for convenience.

`Diversification menu' sets up the parameters for diversification.
You reach it by pressing `m' and then `d' from brews main screen.

The first line tells you if you are looking at NUC, SPOT or GLOBAL
variables diversification. `o' cycles through them, like usual in such
situations.

The mechanism work similar, but not equal:

   * Diversification of NUC variables is only done when a nuc
     reproduces, and only in a certain rate of cases.
     (`diversification rate'). The values are never touched again by
     diversification during the whole life time of the cell. The
     values at time of reproduction will be passed on to the children,
     possibly diversified again. So a child will probably start with
     similar values as the mother cell had.

   * Diversification of SPOT variables however takes place every time
     the spot get's 'called' during evolution. (Well you can restrict
     it to inhabited spots only, if you want). As it is usually used
     as input for the task of a evolutionary experiment the value will
     change with every new life step. A child will very likely find
     values very different from the ones at the spot the mother cell
     lived.

   * Diversification of GLOBAL variables is done once a time step,
     before cycling through all spots of the current world.

Let me explain two technical terms which play a role in all cases:

   * `Diversification range'. This is the maximal possible deviation.
     Diversification will take a random value between zero and this
     value (inclusive) and add or subtract it from the original value.

   * `Diversification closeness'. In fact the value is run more than
     once through the random function. So if you set this value two a
     (small) positive integer > 1 big deviations will get less
     frequent. A value of zero is legitimate (but rarely useful) and
     means, that deviation will always be full positive or negative
     range.

   * `relative'. Diversification of floating point values (not for
     integers) can be done relative by factor. The diversified value
     will be multiplied or divided by a value up to this factor.

   * Of course all the above is only true for variables where
     diversification is switched on at all.


* Menu:

* NUC diversification::         Diversification of NUC local variables.
* SPOT diversification::        Diversification of SPOT local variables.
* GLOBAL diversification::      Diversification of GLOBAL variables.


*Note Scrolling menus::.




File: brew.info, Node: NUC diversification, Next: SPOT diversification, Prev: Diversification menu, Up: Diversification menu

Diversification of NUC variables
--------------------------------

Here you configure diversification of NUC variables:
Beside normal diversification you can configure rare big deviations too.

Upper screen half is for integer nuc variables, lower for floats.
They work very much alike. Please note that not only the diversified values,
but also the parameters for diversification are integers or floats themselves.

   * `Rate'. If rate is set to 1/4 diversification will be done on
     every 4th reproduction, statistically speaking of course. (*Note
     Scale input::).

   * `Range'. Maximal possible deviation in each direction.

   * `Relative'. Maximal factor/divider (only for floats).
 
   * `Closeness'. The bigger this value, the less big deviations.

   * `Sporadic'. (Usually much smaller) rate of sporadic big
     deviations. (*Note Scale input::).

   * `(sporadic) Range'. Range of sporadic deviations. Usually much
     bigger than normal diversification range this allows rare *big*
     value changes. This can be helpful to find isolated islands in a
     value map.


The rest of the menu lets you set the bits for the global diversification
mask for each nuc diversificable variable.
*Note Variable names::, for info on these variables.

Only variables with global *and* individual switch on can get
diversified at all.




File: brew.info, Node: SPOT diversification, Next: GLOBAL diversification, Prev: NUC diversification, Up: Diversification menu

Diversification of SPOT variables
---------------------------------

The configuration of SPOT diversification is very similar to the one
for nucs. It has less options though.

Please refer to *Note NUC diversification::, for more infos.

Please don't forget that you must configure much smaller values here
for a similar effect due to the differences in the inner working of
spot and nuc diversification.

You can restrain spot diversification to inhabited spots. This might
be worth considering for speed reasons, spot diversification will be
done *very* often if you use it.




File: brew.info, Node: GLOBAL diversification, Prev: SPOT diversification, Up: Diversification menu

Diversification of GLOBAL variables.
------------------------------------

This feature is implemented as a convenience to allow an easy set up
of some simple experiments.

The configuration of GLOBAL diversification is very similar to the one
for nucs or spots.

Please refer to *Note NUC diversification::, for more infos.




File: brew.info, Node: Mutation menu, Next: Gene pools menu, Prev: Diversification menu, Up: Users manual

Mutation menu
=============

Here you configure options for the mutation process.
You reach it from brews main screen by pressing `M'.


   * `How often to mutate'. This rate determines in how many cases a
     cell reproduction will lead to mutation of the genome. (*Note
     Scale input::).

   * `Mutation TYPES'. There are different types and sub-types of
     mutation *Note Mutation types menu::. Here you can edit the
     relative probabilities of each type to occur. *Note Probability
     lists::.

   * `Stack turning point'. Genes are normal Forth words and do use
     the Forth stack of course. Mutation has to take care about stack
     balance (and does some primitive type checking too). This is used
     here to influence the possible complexity of the generated gene
     sequences. Mutation knows about the stack aim it has to reach
     regarding depth and stack types. When depth is more than 'stack
     turning point' items off the desired aim, mutation only uses
     genes that don't make it worth. Don't choose too big values or
     the generated gene code will be very different to understand and
     mutation might have difficulty to find to an end. Mutation
     normally terminates, when the stack aim is reached.

   * `Mutations threshold'. Most of the times the stack aim would
     already be reached without inserting any genes at all. So we have
     to insert something to let the process start. So 'stack turning
     point' and such is not respected before 'mutations threshold'
     gene items are inserted. Normally a very small number is best for
     that value.

   * `Size limit for genomes in items'. If the gene pool is not too
     much out of balance regarding stack types mutation should find to
     an end without building too long gene sequences, but you cannot
     be sure about. As evolutionary programming tries out literally
     hundreds of millions of mutations it could get stuck sooner or
     later in a endless mutation. If the gene pool is out of balance
     this will often be the case. So we have this upper size limit as
     a safety belt. If a mutation passes over limit, brew throws and
     restarts the mutation all over again. Brew issues a message about
     it, because it's not considered normal to happen.

   * `RING/quiet'. Switch ringing the bell in case of exceeding genome
     size limit (see above).

   * `Trial phase'. Length of the so called 'trial phase' in
     generations. Each newly mutated gene has to survive trial phase
     before it will get compiled and possibly be put into the gene
     pool. (*Note Trial phase::). Genes on trial will not be mutated
     further.

   * `Include produced genomes as genes'. If this is switched on
     generated genomes that survive trial phase get put in a genomes
     list. The relative probabilities get increased every time a cell
     with this genome is reproduced. The genomes can be used as genes
     or revitalised as genomes from now on.

   * `nuc bit masks'. Diversification uses bit masks in the nuc for
     which variables to diversify or not. Mutation changes these
     masks, setting a bit for each nuc user variable used by a genome.
     Old brew versions did (deliberately) not reset these masks, so a
     nuc variable continued to be diversified from the moment any
     ancestors nuc genome ever set it. The new genomes masks did get
     ORed with the nucs maps. Switching to `Set nuc bit masks
     absolutely' resets them after each mutation.

   * `Diversification of variables'. As mutation and diversification
     are similar processes there is a link to the diversification menu
     here. (*Note Diversification/Mutation::).


* Menu:

* Probability lists::           Pools of functions with different probabilities
* Mutation types menu::         Different types and sub-types of mutation




File: brew.info, Node: Probability lists, Next: Mutation types menu, Prev: Mutation menu, Up: Mutation menu

Probability lists
-----------------

At some places brew uses pools of functions with different relative
probabilities to be (randomly) selected. Examples are the different
types of mutations or gene pools. These `probability lists' can be
nested one into the other.

Example (mutation types):
mutation-types  items: 6    Edit relative probabilities.

1000    top-level-insertion
1000    top-level-replacement
3000    snip-types                      * nested list *
2000    top-level-address-replacemnt
1000    top-level-token-replace
100     restart-from-scratch

The values given in the first column are relative probabilities to get
selected by the random selection mechanism. This means that when a
mutation type will be used the first two types will have the same
relative probability to be chosen, while `snip-types' will be three
times as frequent and so on.

Note that `snip-types' will recurse on the nested probability list
when taken, to determine the final winner. Nesting levels are not
limited.

You change relative probabilities by selecting the entry.

In the case of nested lists you select just like the other entries to
determine the relative probability that (any) one entry of the nested
list would be chosen. To descend one level and set the relative
probabilities *within* the nested pool, select `* nested list *'.

The absolute size of the probability values has no influence only the
relative size has meaning and only within the current nesting level.

Selecting the name of an item shows you it's definition.

Depending the number of items this menu is likely to be a scrolling
one (*Note Scrolling menus::).




File: brew.info, Node: Mutation types menu, Prev: Probability lists, Up: Mutation menu

Mutation types menu
-------------------

There are different mutation types (and sub-types).
Here you configure relative probabilities of each type to happen.

   * `top-level-insertion'. This mutation type inserts a new gene
     sequence at a random position of the original sequence. Brew
     chooses a random position, determines the number and type of
     stack values there and builds a gene sequence that ends having
     the same number and type of stack items but possibly different
     values. Finally it splices the three gene sequences together to a
     new genome. This is the main gene building type, that can start
     from a empty (noop) sequence.

   * `top-level-replacement'. This type of mutation replaces a random
     gene sequence within a genome by another (new) one. Brew picks a
     random gene sequence from the genome and adapts end points such,
     that the end points do not cross conditional levels or somesuch.
     It determines the number and types of stack items at both end
     points and builds a new sequence having the same stack effect
     regarding number and type of items, but possibly changed values.
     So an address might very well have been replaced by another
     address or an integer number by another one. Just the count and
     type of stack items remain unchanged. Finally it splices the
     three gene sequences together to the new genome. This type helps
     optimising gene sequences that have already proven some
     usefulness.

   * `snip-types'. This family of mutation types determine a gene
     sequence within the genome having no overall stack effect
     regarding stack item number and types. The sequence might change
     stack *values*, though. The sequence is just omitted in the
     resulting genome. Together with scoring on code length this helps
     cutting useless gene sequences out of long genomes. Snip types
     come as the following sub types (select `* nested list *' to
     adapt probabilities):

        - `top-level-random-snip'. Look for a random starting point.
          Determine all possible ending points and take a random one.

        - `top-level-short-snip'. Look for a random starting point.
          Take the shortest possible (non empty) sequence to snip
          away.

        - `top-level-long-snip'. Look for a random starting point.
          Determine all possible ending points and take the longest
          possible sequence to be left out.

        - `top-level-snip-IF-ELSE-branch'. Brew can construct
          conditional IF-THEN or IF-ELSE-THEN structures, so it must
          be able to deconstruct them. This snip type chooses a random
          IF-ELSE-THEN structure and eliminates one of the branches,
          leaving the other in the genome without a condition. IF
          branches without ELSE either get snipped away completely or
          get executed unconditionally, eliminating the condition.
          This mutation type just drops the flag and leaves the work
          to eliminate the flag producing gene sequence to other snip
          types. (Brew can not know if the flag producing code has any
          side effects).

   * `top-level-address-replacemnt'. Replace a gene that gives an
     address (most likely some kind of variable) by another one that
     does so. Start at a random point and search towards the end of
     the genome for a gene giving a address. Take the first one found
     restarting from genomes start if necessary. Take a random gene
     giving an address (most likely another variable) as replacement.
     Note that the gene might eventually be replaced by itself. This
     mutation type is a special variety of the next (more generic)
     case. It exists as a separate type due to the special importance
     of addresses (variables). The address replacement type helps
     finding useful variables.

   * `top-level-token-replace'. Take a random gene item, replace it by
     one having the same stack effect regarding stack types (but
     probably different actual stack values). Works very much like
     address replacement above, but accepts any stack effect, not only
     address givers. The type helps optimising genomes that already
     might have developed some usefulness.

   * `restart-from-scratch'. This type throws out the whole genome and
     restarts from scratch by doing top-level-insertion on a empty
     sequence. The type tries to help breaking out of evolutionary
     dead end streets or might sometimes bring in completely new
     approaches to solve the given task. You will typically set this
     type to a pretty low probability.

   * `rebirth'. The genome is replaced by an old one out of a list of
     successful genomes. This gives a distinct species another chance.
     Brew can automatically adapt relative probabilities of the
     genomes based on reproduction count, so successful ones get
     reincarnated more frequently. (*Note Genome pool::).




