Fetching floats from memory
---------------------------

Brew stores all floats as dfloats (double-precision IEEE
floating-point format) for compatibility reasons.

   - ` df ( A-r )'. Read double-precision IEEE floating-point value.

   - ` f-take ( A-r )'. Read double-precision IEEE floating-point
     value actually 'taking it away' from the address (storing zero
     there).




File: brew.info, Node: Store float values, Next: Float stack manipulation, Prev: Read float values, Up: Gene primitives

Fetching floats from memory
---------------------------

Brew stores all floats as dfloats (double-precision IEEE
floating-point format) for compatibility reasons.

   - ` df! ( rA- )'. Store float as double-precision IEEE
     floating-point value at address A.

   - ` df+! ( rA- )'. Add float to the float stored at address A and
     store the sum as double-precision IEEE floating-point value at A.

   - ` df-! ( rA- )'. Subtract a float from the float stored at
     address A and store result as double-precision IEEE
     floating-point value at A.




File: brew.info, Node: Float stack manipulation, Next: Nuc and spot floats, Prev: Store float values, Up: Gene primitives

Arranging items on the float stack
----------------------------------

   - ` fdup ( r-rr )'. Clone topmost float stack item.

   - ` fdrop ( r- )'. Forget topmost float stack item.

   - ` fswap ( rr-rr )'. Exchange the two topmost float stack items.

   - ` fover ( rr-rrr )'. Copy second float stack item to the top.

   - ` frot ( rrr-rrr )'. Rotate third float stack item to the top.

   - ` drop(float-pointer) ( A- )'. Forget address of float on top of
     data stack.




File: brew.info, Node: Nuc and spot floats, Next: Gene conditionals, Prev: Float stack manipulation, Up: Gene primitives

Float variables local to a nuc or spot
--------------------------------------

These variables are the floating point versions of nuc and spot
variables. *Note Nuc and spot variables::, for more informations. Brew
always uses double-precision IEEE floating point format when storing
float values in memory for compatibility reasons. Float variables have
an additional 'f' or 'df' in their name. Some examples:

   - ` f-organ-A ( -A )'. Gives address of first read/write nuc local
     floating point variable.

   - ` f-parameter-B-f ( -r )'. Gives value of second read only nuc
     local floating point variable.

   - ` A-f-quality ( -A )'. Gives address of first read/write spot
     local floating point variable.

   - ` C-f-property ( -r )'. Gives value of third read only spot local
     floating point variable.




File: brew.info, Node: Gene conditionals, Next: Floating point comparison, Prev: Nuc and spot floats, Up: Gene primitives

Conditionally executing gene sequences
--------------------------------------

Gene sequences can contain `IF ELSE THEN' structures like other Forth
code conditionally executing alternatives depending on numerical
comparisons and such. Please note that these structures take the form
of `[IF] [ELSE] [THEN]' during trial phase, as code is interpreted
(not yet compiled) then. Of course brew takes care about that.

   - `g-IF-ELSE-THEN ( C-)' is a pseudo gen, which is never executed,
     but triggers insertion of a `IF ELSE THEN' structure. Setting
     relative probability of this pseudo gene in a gene pool therefore
     influences frequency of `IF ELSE THEN' structures relative to
     other flag taking genes (like `AND' or `OR'). (*Note Probability
     lists::).

   - `IF ( C-)', `[IF] ( C-)'. Conditional branch.
   - `ELSE', `[ELSE]'. Starts alternative sequence.
   - `THEN', `[THEN]'. Ends conditional structure.

   - ` 0= ( n-C)'. True if n is zero.

   - ` 0< ( n-C)'. True if n is below zero.

   - ` 0> ( n-C)'. True if n is positive and not zero.

   - ` = ( nn-C)'. True if the two integers are equal.

   - ` > ( nn-C)'. True if the first integer is bigger.

   - ` < ( nn-C)'. True if the first integer is smaller.

   - ` within ( nnn-C)'. True if the first integer is at least as big
     as the second one, but smaller than the third (topmost) one.

   - ` AND ( CC-C)'. True if both flags are true.

   - ` OR ( CC-C)'. True if at least one flag is true.

   - ` XOR ( CC-C)'. True if exactly one flag is true.




File: brew.info, Node: Floating point comparison, Next: Genome pool, Prev: Gene conditionals, Up: Gene primitives

Conditions based on floating point values
-----------------------------------------

   - ` f< ( rr-C)'. 

   - ` f> ( rr-C)'. 

   - ` f0< ( r-C)'. 

   - ` f0= ( r-C)'. 




File: brew.info, Node: Genome pool, Prev: Floating point comparison, Up: Gene primitives

Genome pools
------------

Brew can put successfully tested genes into a genome pool.
Switch that on or off in `Mutation menu'.
*Note Mutation menu::.

Genome pools serve two distinct purposes:

   * `Genomes as gene building blocks'. Whole genomes that have proven
     to be useful can be reused like gene primitives to build new
     genes.

   * `Revitalisation of old genomes'. Sometimes useful genomes
     disappear by accident during an evolution. You can give them
     another chance by randomly re-introduce some of them again.
     (*Note Mutation types menu::).


Brew increases the relative probability of each genome every time
a cell with this genome get's reproduced. So successful genomes
will be used more often than less successful ones. This mechanism
is switched by the same switch as mentioned above.
*Note Probability lists::.




File: brew.info, Node: Gene edit menu, Next: Scanning nucs, Prev: Gene primitives, Up: Users manual

Examining and editing genes and whole genomes.
==============================================

You are presented a somehow formatted output of the genomes Forth
code. If you select a sub-gene, you will be put (recursively) in the
menu regarding the sub-gene, or presented gene information, if it is a
gene primitive.

Selecting the genomes name, or pressing `e' will write the genome to a
file and call and external editor (defined in `compile-options.fs') on
it. You can change this Forth file as you want to, save it and leave
the editor. Brew will check your input and inform you if it finds a
problem. Otherwise it will replace the nucs genome with your input and
set the nuc on trial. (*Note Trial phase::). All your used Forth words
must be defined already as genes. Brew will inform you, if you do use
a word that isn't. Have a look at some examples in *Note Genes
files::, if you want to define new gene primitives. (You could define
genes from the Forth input line, if you want to. *Note Using Forth in
menus::).




File: brew.info, Node: Scanning nucs, Next: Scanning spots, Prev: Gene edit menu, Up: Users manual

Scanning nucs
=============

If you press `n' in brews main screen you get to a menu displaying
information about (all living) nucs. For each nuc variable you will
see a line displaying minimal, maximal and average value. (*Note
Scrolling menus::). At one given time either integer or floating point
variables are displayed. Toggle between them with `o' as usual, or by
selecting the entry in the title line. (BTW: If you select one kind of
variables brew will assume that you are interested in this type. So
the display of i.e. `Nuc menu' will also switch to the same kind.
*Note Nuc menu::).

The same menu get's used to display statistical informations about nuc
subsets. The title line indicates what variable type gets displayed
and if all nucs or only a subset where scanned.


You see a bunch of lines similar to the following:

generation              min: 1417         max: 1483         average: 1455
genome-generation       min: 0            max: 1098         average: 347
code-cost               min: 100          max: 1699         average: 435
energy                  min: 403          max: 1105         average: 727


Selecting a `min' `max' or `average' value will port you to
a nuc subset screen of the nucs having the value in question.
*Note Menu nuc subsets::.

Selecting a variable name shows you a more detailed view of the
distribution of values of the variable as a simple ASCII bar graph:

                *
                *
                *
                *
                *
                **
                ***       *
                ***       *
                ****     **
                **** *   **
                ******* *****
                *************
                *************  *
       *      ***************  *   *
    ** **     ***************  **  *
   *******   ********************  *
 * ******* * ***********************  * ***
 ************************************ * ****        *
************************************* ************ **  *       *
*****************************************************.****.....*.. *...*.     .
-129        scanning: energy                       vertical range: 69      2260

Selecting a bar of this display type will port you to a `Menu nuc
subsets' with the value range in question, to do more analysis or so.
*Note Menu nuc subsets::.


*Note Menu step display::, for a way to display this type of
information in real time while brewing. You'll find some additional
information there too.


If you display floating point variables you will see lines like:

f-organ-A         min: 0          max: 3.1415926536  avr: .0436332313    .r..

There are four signs at the right border, either dots or `-r+?', which
represent negative infinity, real values, positive infinities and
NANs. A dot means that no values of this type exist. The above line
says, that *f-organ-A* of all scanned nucs did contain a real value,
no infinities or NANs. Selecting the sign will display counts for each
value type, a line for each scanned floating point variable:

Type counts:        -infinity:     real:          +infinity:     nan:

f-organ-A           0              72             0              0

Selecting a title entry like `-infinity' will port you to a nuc subset
menu with nucs that have i.e. negative infinities in any one of their
nuc float variables. As an exception `real' chooses nucs that have
*only* real float values.

Selecting a number, let's say the +infinity count for f-organ-C goes to
the nuc subsets with f-organ-C being +infinity.
*Note Menu nuc subsets::, *Note Menu spot subsets::, for documentation.

Toggle back with `o', or by selecting `Type counts'.




File: brew.info, Node: Scanning spots, Next: Configurable actions, Prev: Scanning nucs, Up: Users manual

Scanning spots
==============

If you press `w' from brews main screen you'll get to a menu
displaying statistical data over all spots. The same menu get's used
at different locations to display statistics about different spot
subsets. (*Note Scrolling menus::).

It works exactly as the corresponding menu for nuc statistics.
*Note Scanning nucs::, for more information.




File: brew.info, Node: Configurable actions, Next: Menu current genomes, Prev: Scanning spots, Up: Users manual

Do something on nuc or spot subsets.
====================================

In many situations you might want to do something with a certain class
of nucs or on certain spots only.

Maybe you are especially interested in all nucs having a certain
genome. So you'd like to replace their display function to something
special so you can watch what's happening with them. Or you'd like to
multiply one of the inner variables of all the cells having this
genome with a given scale, set a special condition on all the spots
inhabited by these cells, remove all other cells or whatever might
make sense in the given situation. Brew has functions to do such
things. You can do quite fancy things with these functions and of
course you can record and replay later on what you did just like about
everything in brew. (Just switch recording on before you do it).

As you will see soon, there are menu interfaces on a couple of places
to do such things. If you want to work on nucs having a special genome
as in the examples above, you'd best use the interface from the menu
that deals with (this) genome; if you want to work on cells on a spot
where spot variables reflect a special condition, approach from a menu
that deals with spots. But you can do much fancier things, if you want
to.

So we must configure at least two parts, (and often some more).

   * `Condition'. The condition is the part that defines on which nucs
     or spots (or combinations of both) the action has to be made.
     Sometimes the condition is already preset for you by brew. In the
     above examples you would go to the menu interface of all nucs
     with this genome which would set the condition to work on all the
     nucs having this genome, so you wouldn't have to bother about.
     Conditions might be simple (like: do it on all inhabited spots)
     or more complex needing more parameters (like: do it on all spots
     where a certain quality is smaller than 1765). For real complex
     cases the interface also allows you to enter Forth source to
     determine whether to do it here or not.

   * `Action'. On all spots and/or nucs (depending the situation)
     where `condition' is `TRUE' this action will be taken. Like with
     conditions there are simple actions (like: remove this nuc) and
     more complex ones that need additional parameters (like: multiply
     energy level of these nucs by 5/3). You can enter fancy actions
     as Forth source at run time. Whatever you'll do, if recording is
     on, it will be recorded of course.


Depending the situation you are prompted for nuc or spot related
conditions and actions, or both:
* Menu:

* Simple nuc conditions::       Defining simple nuc subsets.
* Simple spot conditions::      Defining simple spot subsets.

Extended conditions requiring parameters and a comparison:
* Extended conditions::         Spot or nuc subsets based on comparisons.

Actions to be done on the defined subset:
* Generic nuc/spot actions::    Doing something on spot or nuc subsets.
* Nuc specific actions::        Doing something on nuc subsets.

* Defining maybe-do actions::   The menu interface to conditional actions.

Generic interface to act on a nuc subset:
* Menu nuc subsets::            Menu interface to act on nuc subsets.
* Menu spot subsets::           Menu interface to act on spot subsets.


Please use these advanced functions with great care.

Brew assumes that you know what you are doing here and does not even
try to prevent you from doing the most stupid possible things with
this feature.... So if you tell brew to multiply the action pointer
(`xt') of all nucs genome by say 7/9 it will do it obediently ;-)

Brew does it's best in many places to prevent you from doing stupid
mistakes, but please don't rely on that. Here it does not do
*anything* like that. Did I make that clear?




File: brew.info, Node: Simple nuc conditions, Next: Simple spot conditions, Prev: Configurable actions, Up: Configurable actions

Simple conditions defining a nuc subset.
----------------------------------------

These conditions do not require any parameters.

   * `true'. Do with everybody.

   * `selected?'. Do with all selected nucs.

   * `on-trial?'. Do with all nucs in trial phase.

   * `fertile?'. Do with all nucs that would have enough energy to
     reproduce.

   * `will-die?'. Do with all nucs that will die this life step.




File: brew.info, Node: Simple spot conditions, Next: Extended conditions, Prev: Simple nuc conditions, Up: Configurable actions

Simple conditions defining a spot subset.
-----------------------------------------

These conditions do not require any parameters.

   * `everywhere'. Unconditionally do everywhere.

   * `inhabited?'. Do on all inhabited spots.

   * `empty?'. Do on all spots that are *not* inhabited.




File: brew.info, Node: Extended conditions, Next: Generic nuc/spot actions, Prev: Simple spot conditions, Up: Configurable actions

Extended conditions comparing two values
----------------------------------------

The condition is based on the comparison of two values.
These conditions do require additional parameters and the comparison:

   * `2-variables'. The flag is computed through comparison of the
     values of two spot or nuc variables, which you should select
     next. Of course you can also see variables hidden to the genes
     like `secrets'. You can act like a god in this virtual universe
     ;-)

   * `variable-number'. The flag is computed through comparison of a
     spot or nuc variable against a numeric value. You should select
     the variable and set the threshold value next.

   * `variable-within'. The value of a variable is chequed to be
     within two border values. The lower border is inclusive, the
     upper exclusive. So `0 3 WITHIN' is true for 0, 1 and 2, but not
     for 3. The flag is compared against `true', so use `=' for values
     that are within the range and `<>' for all values that are
     outside range as comparison (see below).

   * `function-number'. The return value of a function (like the score
     of a cell) is compared to a numeric value.

   * `function-within'. The return value of a function is tested if it
     is between two given numeric values.

   * `evaluate-expr'. Select this if you want to define your own
     condition as Forth source. Please take care to use nuc local
     variables exclusively in situations where the nuc is defined at
     all.... The source will be evaluated on all spots and/or nucs
     (depending the situation) and must return *two* stack items to be
     run through the following comparison.


     All the above functions have a floating point version like
     `df-variable-number'. The following words work on dfloat
     variables only to test value types:

   * `df-var-real?'. True if the value is real.

   * `df-var-inf?'. True for infinities of both signs.

   * `df-var-pos-inf?'. True for positive infinity.

   * `df-var-neg-inf?'. True for negative infinity.

   * `df-var-nan?'. True if it is not a number (NAN).


   * `Comparison'. The above functions give two values which are
     compared by one of the following comparisons:

        * `<'. Do it if first value is smaller.

        * `<='. Do it if first value is smaller or equal.

        * `>'. Do it if first value is bigger.

        * `>='. Do it if first value is bigger or equal.

        * `='. Do it if both values are equal.

        * `<>'. Do it if the values are different.


Please note, that of all the above there are distinct versions for
integer and floating point data. (Brew tries to select the right
version depending on the situation, but don't rely too much on that).




File: brew.info, Node: Generic nuc/spot actions, Next: Nuc specific actions, Prev: Extended conditions, Up: Configurable actions

Generic nuc/spot actions
------------------------


   * `set-variable'. Set a variable to a given value. You should
     select the variable and enter the value next.

   * `add-to-variable'. Add a value to a given variable. You should
     select the variable and enter the value next.

   * `sub-from-variable'. Subtract a value from a given variable. You
     should select the variable and enter the value next.

   * `scale-variable'. Multiply a given variable by a scale (like
     1/2). You should select the variable and enter the scale next.
     (*Note Scale input::).

   * `evaluate-do'. Select this item to define your own action as
     Forth source. Your input will be interpreted on all spots/nucs
     where the condition fits. The function is not allowed to access
     stack items it did not put there itself and must not leave
     something on the stack. Please take care to use nuc local
     variables exclusively in situations where the nuc is defined at
     all....


Please note, that of all the above there are distinct versions for
integer and floating point data. (Brew tries to select the right
version depending on the situation, but don't rely too much on that).




File: brew.info, Node: Nuc specific actions, Next: Defining maybe-do actions, Prev: Generic nuc/spot actions, Up: Configurable actions

Nuc specific actions
--------------------

In addition to the generic actions on nuc and/or spot variables you
can program the following nuc specific actions:

   * `select-nuc'. Select nuc.

   * `de-select-nuc'. De-select nuc.

   * `toggle-selection'. Toggle selection status of the nuc.

   * `remove-nuc'. Remove the nuc.




File: brew.info, Node: Defining maybe-do actions, Next: Menu nuc subsets, Prev: Nuc specific actions, Up: Configurable actions

Defining maybe-do actions
-------------------------

I call this mechanism of conditionally executing user defined actions
`maybe-do'. The menu interface to set it all up looks slightly
different depending on the situation. In some cases half of the job is
already invisibly done, like setting the condition or action part. A
typical interface might look like this before you define anything:

Setup condition and action first.
Simple condition:    false
What to do:          noop

`Simple condition' switches between simple and extended conditions.
The rest is trivial, you will find out how it works. After you have done
your configuration it might look similar to this:

DO something on some spots: Please use carefully...
Extended condition:  2-variables  A-quality  B-quality  >
What to do:          scale-variable  food  with  3/2

Selecting the first line of the example, will actually *do* it now.




File: brew.info, Node: Menu nuc subsets, Next: Menu spot subsets, Prev: Defining maybe-do actions, Up: Configurable actions

Menu interface to act on a nuc subset
-------------------------------------

This menu is the user interface to use the `maybe-do' functions on
nucs. *Note Configurable actions::, for an explanation what it does
and how to configure it.

After defining the condition you can display and analyse (scan) all
nucs that fulfils it. The title line of the menu gives the count of
nucs that meet the condition. If an action is defined, you can execute
it on each nuc of the subset.

   * `DO IT'. Do the user defined action on each nuc that fulfils the
     condition.

   * `Show subset'. Show a world map with the subset coloured.

   * `Show on range'. If it makes sense in the given context brew
     offers you a map to see if nucs fall below, within or above a
     given range.

   * `Scan this subset'. Give a summary about nuc variable values or
     more detailed ASCII bar graphs about value distribution on each
     variable. *Note Scanning nucs::, for a description. Called from
     this entry data is collected from nucs fulfilling the condition
     only.

   * `Scan nucs'. Same but with data from *all* nucs for comparisons.

   * `Scan world'. Scan over all spots. Not directly related, but
     useful sometimes. *Note Scanning spots::, for a description how
     it works.




File: brew.info, Node: Menu spot subsets, Prev: Menu nuc subsets, Up: Configurable actions

Menu interface to act on a spot subset
--------------------------------------

This menu is the user interface to use the `maybe-do' functions on
spots. *Note Configurable actions::, for an explanation what it does
and how to configure it.

It works on spots analogous to the `Menu nuc subsets'.

*Note Menu nuc subsets::, for more information.




File: brew.info, Node: Menu current genomes, Next: Menu select nucs, Prev: Configurable actions, Up: Users manual

Menu current genomes
====================

Pressing `U' (or `u' as a shortcut) from brews main screen
takes you to the `Menu current genomes'. This menu deals with the
genomes of all currently living cells. (*Note Scrolling menus::).
The start of the menu screen might look similar to this:

Menu current genomes.                  Genomes of living cells: 79

genome-id:   genome:      count:       cost:        max generations:

0          * noop         948          100          36
2            g-2 t:61     158          287259       26
3            g-3          314          3199         34
4            g-4          10           500          18
7            g-7 t:2      13           500          18
14           g-14 t:3     11           400          15
16           g-16         13           5198         24
18           g-18 t:5     16           4397         17
19           g-19 t:1     9            1000         22
23           on trial     21           1400         16
[ ... ]

The title line tells you how many different genomes there are
currently.

The column titles (with the exception of the one for the genome name)
are selectable menu items. If you select them, the display order of
the lines belonging to the single genomes is changed to be based on
the quality in question. Selecting the item again will switch between
ascending and descending sorting. You can also use the key bindings
given below.

The column have the following meaning:

   * `genome-id'. Identification number of the genome. As these
     numbers are given in ascending order it is also a relative
     indicator of the age of this genome.

           Selecting the column title or pressing `i' or `g' will set
     the genome-id to be the key for the order of genome display.
     Selecting it again will switch between ascending and descending
     order.

           Selecting this columns entry of a genome leads to the menu
     for this individual genome. *Note Menu this genome::.

   * `genome'. Name of the compiled genome, if any. As genomes on
     trial have no name yet `on trial' get's displayed instead (see
     genome #23 above). If the genome *has* been compiled, but there
     are still some individuals left in trial phase from before that
     their number gets displayed as `t: <number>' after the name (see
     genome #2 above). (You cannot order display based on genome
     names).

           Selecting this columns entry of a genome will display the
     genomes program code.

   * `count'. Number of living cells with this genome. Press `c' to
     switch to count based display order.

           Selecting this columns entry of a genome will display a
     world map with the cells having this genome coloured.

   * `cost'. Code cost of the genome. This is a function of gene code
     length, so it also tells you something about the relative length
     of the genomes. Press `o' for cOst based display ordering.

           Selecting this columns entry of a genome will display a
     three coloured world map. Cells having the same gene code cost as
     the genome in question are white, cells with shorter code red and
     those with longer code are displayed cyan. *Note Colouring on
     difference::.

   * `max generations'. Check all cells of the same genome for how
     many generations this genome has already survived since last
     mutating it. The *maximal* number of generations found is
     displayed here. Pressing `m' orders display based on this value.

           Selecting this columns entry of a genome will display a
     three coloured world map. Cells having the same genome generation
     cost as displayed in the genome entry in question are white,
     cells with less genome generations red and those with more genome
     generations are displayed cyan. *Note Colouring on difference::.


* Menu:

* Colouring on equality::       Display cells with same amount of a quality.
* Colouring on difference::     Displaying `less', `equal', `more' type info.
* Menu this genome::            Examining all cells having the same genome.


You can look at each listed genome one after the other by pressing one
of the following keys:

   * `<SPACE>' to go to corresponding `Menu this genome'.

   * `l' or `n' to see the genomes Forth code.

   * `.' to call `.gene-info' on the genome. In the case of genomes on
     trial it shows the evaluated Forth code instead.

The `current' line will be indicated by a `*' before genome name, and
go down one line after examining the genome.




File: brew.info, Node: Colouring on equality, Next: Colouring on difference, Prev: Menu current genomes, Up: Menu current genomes

Colouring on equality
---------------------

Brew uses this function to show you all cells which share one special
quality. Brew displays a world map and colours the cells in question.
Similar maps get used to display spot qualities.

If you don't like the colours change `color-selected-fg-xt' and
`color-miss-fg-xt' for foreground colours (showing nucs), respectively
`color-selected-bg-xt' and `color-miss-bg-xt' for background colours
(showing spots) in `my-brew-options.fs'.

As an example brew uses it to show you all cells sharing the same
genome.

*Note World map interaction::, to learn what else you can do here.




File: brew.info, Node: Colouring on difference, Next: Menu this genome, Prev: Colouring on equality, Up: Menu current genomes

Three coloured world maps
-------------------------

Sometimes brew shows you a three coloured world map to indicate which
nucs or spots fall below, inside or above a certain range regarding
some quality in question. Falling `inside' a range can also mean
equality with a single value. Foreground colours code nuc qualities,
background shows the spot like always.

As an example the map could show you all nucs having code cost falling
into a given range (which is about the same as having a certain code
length) in one color, the shorter ones in another, and the longer ones
in a third colour. I call this `Colouring on difference'.


The meanings of the (default) colours (on foreground) are:

   * `magenta'. Lower, less of the quality in question.

   * `white'. Inside range or equal amount of the quality in question.

   * `cyan'. Higher, more of the quality in question.

If you don't like the colours change `color-below-fg-xt',
`color-selected-fg-xt' and `color-above-fg-xt' for the foreground
colours (showing nucs), respectively `color-below-bg-xt',
`color-selected-bg-xt' and `color-above-bg-xt' for the background
colours (showing spots) in `my-brew-options.fs'.


*Note World map interaction::, to learn what else you can do here.




File: brew.info, Node: Menu this genome, Prev: Colouring on difference, Up: Menu current genomes

Menu this genome
----------------

You'll get here normally selecting a entry for a genome from menu
`Menu current genomes'. (Which you reach by pressing `U' in brews main
screen). You cannot come here from brews main screen or from the super
menu, as brew can not know which genome you are interested in.

The menu title shows you the name of the compiled genome (if it is
compiled already) and how many cells share this same genome.


   * `genome GID'. The entry informs you about the genome
     identification number, which is not editable (at least not from
     here). If you select the entry brew will show you the Forth
     program code of the genome.

   * `.gene-info'. This entry gives you more informations about the
     genome.

   * `show cells'. Show a world map with cells having this genome
     coloured. (*Note Colouring on equality::).

   * `show younger/older'. Show a three color world map on age of
     genome relative to this one. (*Note Colouring on difference::).

   * `Scan these nucs'. Get nuc scan information from the nucs sharing
     this genome. The interface works exactly as the generic one, but
     the information of summary and detailed value distribution graphs
     are automatically scanned from these cells only. (*Note Scanning
     nucs::).

   * `Scan all nucs'. Get nuc scan information from *all* nucs. This
     is convenient to compare to the scan results gained from the
     subset of cells with the genome currently examined.

   * `Select these nucs'. Set the `selected' flag in all the nucs
     having this genome. (i.e. when you want to have a easy way to see
     the offspring later on).

   * `clear selection'. Clear the `selected' flag in all the nucs
     having this genome.

   * `toggle selection'. Invert the `selected' flag in all the nucs
     having this genome.

   * `Do something on these nucs'. This is the `maybe-do' interface to
     do something on the subset of nucs sharing this genome. You can
     program actions executed with all these cells or even enter Forth
     source code to be applied on them at run time. Brew already did
     set the condition (to work on nucs with this genome only) for
     you. You just have to select the action. This is an advanced
     feature without safety net. Please use with care. *Note
     Configurable actions::, for more info.




File: brew.info, Node: Menu select nucs, Next: World menu, Prev: Menu current genomes, Up: Users manual

Menu select nucs
================

This menu deals with the selection status of nucs.
You get here from brews main screen by pressing `T'.
The title line tells you how many nucs are selected and how many aren't.


Nucs can be `selected', which just means that a special flag is set
within them. As a part of the nuc this flag is hereditary and will not
be reset by brew without that you ask for it. The flag has no meaning
at all for brew, it is a tool for the user to use for whatever he
likes.

The feature has similar uses as the `maybe-do' functions (*Note
Configurable actions::), but there are some differences:

   * `Persistence'. A nuc once selected stays selected if you do not
     de-select it somehow. This is not always the case with nucs
     fulfilling a certain condition at one moment. At a later moment
     the same nuc might very well fail to fulfil the condition.

   * `Combinations'. The possibility to add, remove and invert
     selections on various (sub) groups of nucs depending on different
     conditions one after another let's you build very complex subsets
     much more easy than you could with a single condition.

   * `Heredity'. The fact that selection status gets transmitted to
     the descendants opens the door to uses that would not be possible
     with the other similar features.


Menu features:

   * `show selected'. Show a world map where all selected cells are
     coloured.

   * `colour'. Configure colour of selected cells in the map described
     above. The default is `red'.

   * `deselect all'. Clear all selections of all cells.

   * `toggle selections'. Invert selections of all nucs.

   * `scan SELECTED nucs'. Statistical informations about all selected
     nucs. (*Note Scanning nucs::).

   * `scan ALL nucs'. Statistical informations about *all* nucs for
     comparisons.


There are two interfaces to the `maybe-do' feature, one for changing
selections based on a condition, the other to do configurable actions
on all selected nucs (*Note Configurable actions::).

   * `Change selections'. This interface gives you the possibility to
     `select', `de-select', `toggle (invert) selection' on all nucs
     fulfilling a freely configurable condition. Click `DO IT' to
     actually change selections in the configured way.

   * `DO on selected nucs'. This interface let's you configure an
     action to be taken on all selected nucs. The condition part
     (being selected) is (invisibly) preset already. Click `DO on
     selected nucs' after configuring to trigger the action.




File: brew.info, Node: World menu, Next: World list menu, Prev: Menu select nucs, Up: Users manual

World menu
==========

This menu gives informations and interfaces to some world wide
settings of the current world. You come here from brew main screen by
pressing `W'.

The menu title line tells you how many dimensions of what size this
world has.


   * `Name'. The first line starts with the worlds name. Select and
     change to whatever you like.

   * `3/5'. Would say that you are in world # 3 of 5.

   * `SELECT'. Change to another world. *Note World list menu::.

   * `REMOVE'. Lets this whole world and all it's cells disappear. The
     compiled genomes will persist, of course (genomes on trial will
     disappear if they do not co-exist in another world, though).

Following items are purely informative, you cannot change them:

   * `spots'. Number of spots in this universe.

   * `living'. How many cells life in this world at the moment.

   * `on trial'. How many cells are currently on trial. Selecting this
     item will show a map of nucs on trial (if any).

   * `selected'. Number of selected cells. Selecting this item will
     show a map of selected nucs (if any).

   * `compiled'. Number of compiled genomes since start of this
     evolution.

   * `max items'. Longest generated genome so far.

   * `qualities'. Number of spot qualities (r/w variables local to the
     spot). (*Note Variable names::). This is configured at compile
     time.

   * `properties'. Number of spot properties (r/o variables local to
     the spot). (*Note Variable names::). This is configured at
     compile time.

   * `secrets'. Number of spot secrets (variables local to the spot,
     invisible to the genome). (*Note Variable names::). This is
     configured at compile time.


The next few lines give information about dimensionality and size of
the current world and let you configure visibility ranges for each
dimension. *Note World size and visibility::.


The following three entries let you configure special actions that
might be needed for some sort of experiments:

   * `spot do'. This function gets called on each spot (after
     diversifying spot variables) before waking up the nuc eventually
     living there. The default function is a noop.

   * `nuc do before'. On inhabited spots this is called (after `spot
     do') just before waking up the nuc. The function defaults to
     noop.

   * `nuc do after'. On inhabited spots this is called after the nuc
     has finished it's job. It is executed wherever a cell was woken
     up, even if the cell died or moved away in this life step. So if
     you write functions to put in here yourself check if the nuc is
     still here before you refer to nuc intern variables). Default is
     a noop.

   * `step do before'. Action done when starting a new step. Default
     is a noop.

   * `step do after'. Action done after finishing a step. Default is a
     noop.


Some interfaces to other world related functions:

   * `Scan world'. Interface to the world scan functions over all
     spots. (*Note Scanning spots::).

   * `Scan nucs'. Interface to the nuc scan functions over all living
     cells. (*Note Scanning nucs::).

   * `Delete all'. This clears the whole current world, initialises
     all world variables, sets all spot variables to zero and removes
     all nucs. After calling this function you have to set at least
     one individual to be able to do something useful. (*Note
     Individuals menu::).

   * `Big bang'. World menu only deals with the current world. There
     can be multiple worlds though, each one having her own structure
     and configuration settings. This leads to the menu to define and
     create another world. (*Note Big Bang menu::).


The rest of the world menu let's you define a action to do on spots
that meet a certain condition (`maybe-do' feature working on spots).
You must configure the condition which spots will be treated and
define the action to take. Then you can select `DO something on some
spots' to trigger the action. Like always in similar cases you can
select amongst simple or more complex conditions and actions or define
your own in Forth program source. On inhabited spots (only) you can
access nuc variables too. (*Note Configurable actions::).




File: brew.info, Node: World list menu, Next: Big Bang menu, Prev: World menu, Up: Users manual

List of worlds
==============

You get to this menu by pressing `O' (like `Other worlds') in brews
main screen. It is a list of all existing brew worlds. Select a world
from the list to enter it.

Brew let's you change world names, and shows you some geometry
information for each world.

   * `clone'. Clone this world including all it's cells and enter the
     cloned one.

   * `remove'. Delete this world and remove all it's inhabitants.

   * `save'. Save this world (without it's cells) to a huge text file.

If you want, you can also create new worlds from this menu.


BTW: As a shortcut in brews main screen you can switch to another
world by pressing the number key of the world you want to enter.




File: brew.info, Node: Big Bang menu, Next: System menu, Prev: World list menu, Up: Users manual

Big Bang menu
=============

This menu let's you define and create another world.

You get here by pressing `B'+`B' (capital `B' twice) from brews main
screen.

The upper half of the menu screen shows you the settings of the
current world, the lower half let's you configure and create another
one. After creating a new world the new one will be the current one.


The second half is the main part of the menu, here you define the
geometrical structure of your new world and the visibility ranges of
each dimension and finally create it. Select `Clone geometry' for same
geometric structure as the current world has.

* Menu:

* World size and visibility::   Current worlds geometry and visibility.
* Big Bang::                    Define and create a new world.

Note that you must configure the settings of the newly created world
to be able to do something with it. At least you must set some living
cells into it to start a new evolution. (*Note Individuals menu::).
Also check visibility ranges in the upper menu half, and configure
them as you like.




File: brew.info, Node: World size and visibility, Next: Big Bang, Prev: Big Bang menu, Up: Big Bang menu

World size and visibility
-------------------------

Brews virtual world can have from one to five (or more) dimensions of
any size. Often only a part of the world will be displayed. You can
configure visibility range for each dimension. Brew does no zooming in
world display, so visibility range in the first two dimensions cannot
exceed screen size (minus info line as last screen line), but of
course it can be like a visibility window in a bigger plane. Higher
dimensions are just projected into the plane taking into account
visibility range of all dimensions. So a cell of a four dimensional
world at coordinates (a,b,c,d) would be displayed at (a,b) provided
all coordinates fall into the visibility range of it's dimension.

If you want to display a world of more than two dimensions you can
choose to show only one layer or a range of layers one over the other.
In the latter case it might be helpful to delay display of each
individual layer to have a chance to understand the three dimensional
structure while the display is building up. The layers can be
transparent or opaque on spots where no cell lives, depending on the
background being displayed or not on empty spots. Background will
always have to be displayed on the first displayed plane, but can be
switched off later. As this sounds all more complicated than it is,
there are some examples further down.

For each dimension you have a line like this:
1 dimension  spots: 80  visible from: 0         to: 80

The entries have the following meaning:

   * `n'th dimension'. Number of dimension.

   * `spots'. Size of dimension range. If `spots' is 80, coordinates
     would go from 0 to 79.

   * `visible from'. Start of visibility range, lowest visible
     coordinate.

   * `visible to'. End of visibility range, highest visible
     coordinate. Note that in the above example visibility would not
     been switched off, because coordinate 80 does not exist and is
     never reached so. This saves some time on a screen where
     everything is visible anyway.

If you have more than two dimensions you will see the following two
entries:

   * `backgr.off'. Coordinate of third dimension after which
     background displaying is switched off. Up to this coordinate
     layers are opaque, after they become transparent.

   * `Delay displaying layers'. Delay (theoretically in milliseconds)
     after displaying a (third dimensions) layer. A pause can help to
     understand the displayed three dimensional structure.


Examples:

Two dimensional world, screen sized on the Linux text console. Fast
and everything is visible: (Might be too small for some types of
experiments).

Current world           spots: 1920
1 dimension  spots: 80  visible from: 0         to: 80
2 dimension  spots: 24  visible from: 0         to: 24
Delay displaying layers:        0


Tree dimensional world, only middle layer visible:

Current world           spots: 19200
1 dimension  spots: 80  visible from: 0         to: 80
2 dimension  spots: 24  visible from: 0         to: 24
3 dimension  spots: 10  visible from: 4         to: 4    backgr.off: 4
Delay displaying layers:        0


Tree dimensional world, all layers visible. Brew displays one layer
after the other, all opaque, and pauses a bit after each layer:

Current world           spots: 19200
1 dimension  spots: 80  visible from: 0         to: 80
2 dimension  spots: 24  visible from: 0         to: 24
3 dimension  spots: 10  visible from: 0         to: 10    backgr.off: 10
Delay displaying layers:        1000


Tree dimensional world, all layers visible. Brew displays one layer
after the other, the first one opaque (to hide previous display), all
the following transparent. Pauses a bit after each layer:

Current world           spots: 19200
1 dimension  spots: 80  visible from: 0         to: 80
2 dimension  spots: 24  visible from: 0         to: 24
3 dimension  spots: 10  visible from: 0         to: 10    backgr.off: 0
Delay displaying layers:        2000




File: brew.info, Node: Big Bang, Prev: World size and visibility, Up: Big Bang menu

Make a Big Bang
---------------

Here you define the geometry of your new world.

   * `Dimensions'. Dimensionality of the new world. While it is often
     advisable to select a two dimensional screen sized world for
     efficiency reasons you can define worlds from one to five (and
     more) dimensions. Choosing a exaggerated dimensionality will soon
     eat up a lot of memory and CPU power and slow down things too
     much though. You can have as many worlds as you like (provided
     you have enough memory) and each one can have a different
     dimensionality and size, but they all share the same spot
     structure (number and classes of spot variables) which is
     configured at compile time.

   * `dimension range'. Size of range for each dimension. The
     coordinates in this dimension will go from 0 to n-1. Brews world
     wraps at it's borders, if a cell moves in one direction and
     leaves the range in a dimensions range it will reenter the world
     from the opposite side.

   * `make a Big Bang'. After defining dimensionality and ranges for
     all dimensions this entry will appear. Choose it to actually
     create your new world. After the big bang the new world will be
     empty and all the spot variables will have a zero value. The new
     world will automatically become current. You can configure
     visibility ranges now.


In Linux text console (which is the main platform brew is developed
for) it is a good choice to make worlds two dimensional and 80 * 24
sized, to fit the screen.




File: brew.info, Node: System menu, Next: Log files menu, Prev: Big Bang menu, Up: Users manual

System menu
===========

This is the menu for brews system wide settings.
You get there by pressing `S' in brews main screen.


   * `Running in WORLD mode' or `LINEAR mode'. Switches if the cells
     do have a virtual location or not. (*Note Run modes::).

   * `Reset brew'. Reset brew by reading `brew-defaults.fs', do a
     `free-field' and reading `brew-init.fs' again. If you have
     included your personal initialisation files you might want to
     include them too.

   * `Brew version'. Give detailed information about versions of
     different brew parts and about some compile time options. Please
     include this output in bug reports.

   * `Random generator'. Switch random generator and initialise it.
     Sometimes the random generator and/or it's seed has an enormous
     influence on the results. Sometimes the same result turns up
     sooner or later quite independent of the used random generator.
     Brew gives you the possibility to try that out. *Note Selecting
     functions::, for a method to see the definitions of the used
     random generators.

        * `random-BRODIE'. Use the random generator given by Leo
          Brodie in his excellent Forth introduction book `Starting
          FORTH'.

             * `Random seed'. Current value of the random seed.

        * `random-generalised'. Use a more generic random generator.

             * `Random seed'. Current value of the random seed.

             * `Random generator'. Value used internally for random
               number generation.

   * `Can cells change qualities of the future?'. Genes can change
     spot qualities (*Note Variable names::). If this switch is ON the
     change survives a time step, otherwise it only takes effect in
     the present life step

   * `Cell division moves cell mother too?'. Normally the mother cell
     does not move when it divides, only the child is on a new
     location. This switch changes this behaviour. This option exists
     only in `world mode'.

   * `Cell division diversifies cell mother too?'. While the child's
     variables are always possibly diversified the mothers are not.
     This switches diversification of the mother cell.

   * `Cell division mutates cell mother too?'. Mutation normally can
     only happen on the child, but not on the mother cell of a cell
     division. This switch changes that.

   * `Order to call the spots'. To run brews world through a time step
     all the spots are called once, one after the other, at least
     normally. The order to call the spots can be configured here.
     This option exists only in `world mode'.

        * `sequential calling spots forwards'. This is the normal
          setting, it's fastest (for technical reasons) and the only
          setting recommended for 3D views.

        * `sequential calling spots backwards'. This is much slower
          then the other way round and there's no reason beside
          testing influence of this parameter to set it to this value.

        * `randomly calling as many spots as there are'. This is
          probably the slowest setting, but it can be interesting
          sometimes. Note that brew just calls the right number of
          random spots, not caring about if a spot get's called
          several times or if it's omitted.

        * `alternate direction, starting forwards'. This calls the
          spots sequentially, starting forwards. Quite slow.

        * `alternate direction, starting backwards'. This calls the
          spots sequentially, starting backwards. Quite slow.

   * `Save brew variables'. Save all brew variables which means saving
     most initialisations and configurations. Note that cells (edited,
     mutated or set to a spot) are *not* saved by this function. The
     variables are saved as Forth program source. You are prompted for
     a file name relative to `brew/OUTPUT/'.

   * `Save world'. Save all world and spot data to a Forth text file.
     Writes a *huge* file.

   * `Save all nucs'. Save all nucs data to a Forth text file, which
     can get huge, depending on the number of nucs and nuc variables.
     If you include this file later on the nucs will be reproduced and
     set to the same spots they where before, replacing other nucs on
     these spots. Genomes must be defined before, though. Use with
     care.

   * `Include file'. Select a file to be included. Brew does not check
     what you are doing here, it's completely at your own risk. In
     this brew version this also is used to include experiments, which
     might change in future versions. (*Note Experiments::).

   * `World scan'. Statistics about all spot variables. (*Note
     Scanning spots::).

   * `Nuc scan'. Statistics about all nuc variables. (*Note Scanning
     nucs::).

   * `Function keys'. Configure function key bindings.

   * `Use ekey for key input'. If your brew is compiled with ekey
     support you can switch this on and off here in case of input
     difficulties. (In case it only works when switched off, you
     should fix the problem or switch it off as a compile time
     option).

   * `Cursor wraps at borders' or `Cursor stops at borders'. Switch
     between cursor wrapping or stopping, when moving over a screen
     border.

   * `Fix screen size'. Include `configure-console.fs' to fix console
     size problems.

   * `Fix cursor moving problems (beeping)'. If you have problems
     moving the cursor with the arrow keys you can try this function.
     Hope it helps.

   * `Manual'. Call the external manual reader on top node. See the
     entry `Documentation type' below, to switch between info and
     html.

   * `Documentation type'. Select between using `info' or a html
     browser as context sensitive documentation reader.

   * `reader'. Displays information how the docu reader gets called.
     Intended to track problems calling context documentation.

   * `QUIT brew'. Quit brew cleaning up temporary files and informing
     you about produced output files, if any.


The identity number displayed in the title line can be helpful to
identify output files, as the number get's included in file names.


When brew is started with special options (i.e. `COUNTING-WORDS' *Note
Programming tool files::) additional items might show up in system
menu.




File: brew.info, Node: Log files menu, Next: Code file menu, Prev: System menu, Up: Users manual

Log files menu
==============

This menu allows you to switch very detailed what brew should write in
it's log files and what not. You come to this menu by pressing `L' in
brews main screen.


Brew can write very detailed log files about what it does. Actually
this elaborated logging facility is a by-product of my debugging
activities ;-) Debugging evolutionary programming can be quite a
task....

Log files can be an excellent help when you want to understand what
actually happens during an evolutionary session. If you want to do
fancy things like drawing phylogenetic trees of the generated genomes
or such, log files will be a big help. You will probably need to write
some perl scripts to be able to process that amount of data though.

Logging slows brew down a lot, of course.

Please realize that brews log files can grow really big; don't forget
to switch logging back off and delete the log files after use, or your
brand new gigantic hard drive will be full very soon....

I will not explain the format of log files here, as this would take
too much room and time. Just put logging on for some time, if you are
interested in it. I think you should be able to understand the result.


Most of the menu screen is covered by switches what to put in the log
file:

   * `All'. This puts all the switches on. Don't do this ;-)

   * `Most'. This puts nearly all the switches on. Don't do this ;-)

   * `Nothing'. Switches logging back off.

   * `Some'. Switches some basic information on.

   * `spot'. Log when doing a new spot.

   * `birth'. Log each birth of a cell.

   * `death'. Log death of a cell.

   * `organs'. Log value of organs (and other cell variables) before
     and after waking nucs.

   * `meal'. Log how much food each cell got in each life step.

   * `costs'. Log live and gene code costs.

   * `trial'. Log nucs on trial.

   * `movement'. Log movements of nucs.

   * `emergency'. Log population emergencies.

   * `pop-control'. Log working of population control.

   * `step'. Log time steps.

   * `spot-vars'. Log value of spot variables before and after waking
     nucs.

   * `random'. Log state of random generator.

   * `user'. Log user interactions (big brother is watching you).


     Please note that the following mutation logging switches depend
     on each other in ascending order. You cannot switch a lower order
     item off before clearing the higher order switches.

   * `mutation'. Log mutations. (You can't switch that off if a more
     detailed logging switch is on).

   * `m-type'. Log type of mutations. (You can't switch that off if a
     more detailed logging switch is on).

   * `m-some'. Log mutation working with some detail information. (You
     can't switch that off if a more detailed logging switch is on).

   * `m-more'. Log mutation working with a lot of detail informations.
     Can be configured away at compile time for speed reasons. (You
     can't switch that off if a more detailed logging switch is on).

   * `m-much'. Log a real lot of details about the inner working of
     mutations. Can be configured away at compile time for speed
     reasons. (You can't switch that off if a more detailed logging
     switch is on).

   * `log-m-extra'. Log extensive about the detailed inner working of
     mutation. This option is not compiled in by default, only on
     request.


   * `log-empty-spots'. Log spot variables and the like even for empty
     spots. This option is only interesting for debugging and writes
     an awful lot of information. Don't switch it on. This option is
     not compiled in by default, only on request.


   * `Log file'. Log file name. Defaults to
     `brew/OUTPUT/log/brew.log'.

   * `Writing code file'. Link to the code file menu: Write generated
     program code to a file.

   * `Log state'. Write current brew state to the log file in the same
     form as it would appear in a configuration or record file (that
     is as Forth code).


*Note Scrolling menus::.




File: brew.info, Node: Code file menu, Next: Record and Playback, Prev: Log files menu, Up: Users manual

Writing generated program code to a file.
=========================================

Brew can write the produced Forth program code to a file, the so called
`code file'. Code file have normal Forth syntax and should compile
the defined genome when they are included. Beside the code brew can put
some more information (i.e. stack type comments) in the file. This is
the place to configure that.
You'll get here from brews main screen by pressing first `m' and then
`c'.

On a Linux system you can watch mutation and selection at work in real
time by switching to another console and say `tail -f
OUTPUT/FORTH/gene-code.fs'.


The menu gives you the following options:

   * `Writing a human readable code file to the hd is off/ON'.
     Switches writing code files completely off. If switched off, the
     menu will not show any other options.

   * `Code file'. Name of the code file relative to `OUTPUT/FORTH/'.
     The default code file name is `OUTPUT/FORTH/gene-code.fs'.

   * `file on trial SUCCESS'. If you switch that ON genomes will be
     written to the code file when they successfully survive the so
     called `trial phase'. Normally this is the useful setting for
     this switch. The menu will show you some more options when you
     switch this one on.

   * `file ALL MUTATIONs'. Switching this ON will result in putting
     every generated genome in the code file at the time mutation
     creates them. Most of them will be useless or even absurd code.
     As there is more information available during the mutation
     process then after trial phase there are some more choices what
     to put in code files. I don't think these informations are too
     interesting to normal brew users though (But then I don't think a
     `normal' person would ever use brew anyway ;-)


Switches what to put in the code file:
(The first three are compound switches).

   * `ALL'. Switches all information that can be put into code files
     on. It's not that much as with log files, but it makes code files
     quite unreadable. It's more a debugging help.

   * `nothing'. Shortcut to switch everything off if you want to
     restart configuring the individual switches. If you don't want
     any code file at all use the very first option of the menu
     instead.

   * `CODE & stack'. Put Forth program code together with stack type
     symbol comments in the code file. This is usually the recommended
     setting, as you'd better collect other information from the log
     files. Brews stack type symbol comments are similar but not equal
     to the usual Forth stack comments. (*Note Stack type symbols::).

   * `STRUCTURE only'. Include only structure building words like `IF'
     `ELSE' and `THEN'. All other code is omitted. For quick
     inspection of the structure of genomes. You can't compile the
     resulting pseudo code, of course.


   * `code'. Normally you'd want code to be in the code files, won't
     you?

   * `stack'. Put stack type symbol comments, similar but not equal to
     the usual Forth stack comments into the code file. I think this
     makes the code a bit easier to read (*Note Stack type symbols::).

   * `mutation-type'. You might be curious what type of mutation
     generated the genome in question. This switch allows this
     information to be written to the code file.

   * `structures'. If you switch this on, but `code' off, you will see
     structure building words, without code in between.

   * `frames'. By `frame' I mean a gene code segment like a
     conditional clause, an inserted sequence or similar. Frames can
     be nested at will as long as a nested frame is always contained
     as a whole in the other one.

   * `depth&cost'. Informations about minimal and maximal stack depth
     so far and about accumulated code costs go into the code file.

   * `step,spot,id'. Put information about time (step), location
     (spot) and mother cell (id) where the mutation happened into the
     code file. This makes it especially easy when you want to
     associate with informations from log files.

   * `item-numbers'. Put a item number for each used gene primitive.




File: brew.info, Node: Record and Playback, Next: Compile time options, Prev: Code file menu, Up: Users manual

Brews record and playback feature.
==================================


You get to the Record and Playback menu by pressing `R' from brews
main screen.


Evolutionary programming can be mean: You set up a new experiment,
make some preliminary tests with a few options and see exciting
results within very short time. Then you try to find even better
defaults, only to realize that the defaults you took have been very,
very lucky, but unfortunately you have forgotten them. If only brew
could remember them for you....

Or you have done a lot of configuring and want to do a series of
experiments starting from that point, but you don't want to do all
this configuring all over again and again....

For such situation brew has a feature to record and playback just
about every user interaction possible in brew (It will even catch a
lot of things you might have configured using configuration files).

If you want the thing to work it will be enough in most cases just to
switch recording on. This must be done *before* you put any cells into
the play. Brew will automatically record brews state in the moment you
switched recording on, catch and record every change you do to this
state and every command you pass to brew.

Brews record files are ordinary Forth source text files which can be
edited by hand of course.

Use brews recording feature
   - to make configuration files by configurating through the menu
     interface and saving the result as a record file.
   - to record evolutionary sessions to be able to replay them, try
     variations or such.
   - just in case you select some very lucky starting conditions by
     accident. Recording does not cost much. As it only saves user
     interactions it has nothing to do during the actual evolutionary
     process and does not slow it down or so. So you can switch it on
     just in case....
   - to record a evolutionary session as a benchmark for your hardware
     or Forth system. There are some special tools to make benchmarks.
   - to make a demo which you'll send to me that I can see what people
     do with my program ;-)

* Menu:

* Recording from scratch::      How to record an evolutionary session.
* Record after playback::       How to continue recording on an existing file.
* Record benchmark::            Recording to be used as benchmark.
* Playback::                    Playing back a recorded session.




File: brew.info, Node: Recording from scratch, Next: Record after playback, Prev: Record and Playback, Up: Record and Playback

How to record an evolutionary session starting from scratch.
------------------------------------------------------------

When you switch recording on in the `Record and Playback menu' brew
saves it's current configuration to the record file, including all the
settings you changed trough the menu interface or configuration files.
It does *not* save the current state of the world and it's inhabitants
though. If you want to record an evolutionary session you must start
with an *empty* world. So brew clears the world when you switch
recording on and includes a command to do so in the record file. So if
you play back the file later it will start with an empty world too.
Note that in both cases all the contents of the current world (prior
to switching recording on) are lost.

   * `Record'. Switch recording on here to restarts a session from
     scratch. Brew removes all inhabitants of the current world and
     resets all world variables. It removes all other worlds
     completely.

   * `Please give record file name'. Brew reacts by asking you for a
     file name relative to `OUTPUT/rec-play/' and defaults to
     `OUTPUT/rec-play/brew-recorded.fs'.

   * `Now you should select an individual and set it to a spot'. Brew
     informs you now about the next necessary step and puts you in the
     individuals menu to select and eventually edit an individual.
     (*Note Individuals menu::).

   * `Now go back to the main screen and set the individual'. Brew
     guides you here, just do what it tells you to do ;-)

   * After that you continue just as you would have done without
     recording. You can use all the usual brew features and functions
     and everything (with very few exceptions *Note Using Forth in
     menus::) should be recorded automatically now as long as you do
     not switch recording off. Everything should be re-played exactly
     as it happened during recording if you choose the record file
     later on as a playback file.

The menu now looks like this:

   * `Record is ON'. Switch it off here when you'll have finished (but
     not before that).

   * `Record file: brew-recorded.fs'. That's just informative now. You
     cannot change that during recording.

   * `assert state (for benchmark creation)'. Put an entry about the
     current state of evolution including a check sum over all spots
     and one over all nucs which will be chequed at playback time.
     Brew will tell you if something went wrong during playback,
     silently proceed otherwise. For benchmarks and for debugging.

        * `You can give a comment'. The comment will be displayed
          together with the information if everything went ok or not
          at playback time. Use a *very short* description about what
          happened just before the state check.

   * `save state (normally only diffs get saved)'. This saves *all*
     brew variables, not only those that have changed. Use this to
     create initialisation files, but also if you intend to edit
     (especially cut) the recorded file later on by hand.

   * `record comment'. Insert remarks as a comment into the record
     file. These notes will *not* be displayed during play back.

        * `Give a comment to be included in the record file' Enter
          your text here.

   * `message input'. Edit a short message that will be displayed in
     the last line (`info line') during playback.

        * `Give a message to be displayed during playback'. The
          message must be shorter than one full line.

        * `For how many steps do you want the message to be
          displayed?'. Give an estimated number, you can always edit
          that in the record file by hand, if you don't like the
          result.




File: brew.info, Node: Record after playback, Next: Record benchmark, Prev: Recording from scratch, Up: Record and Playback

How to append to an existing recorded file.
-------------------------------------------

After playing back a recorded evolutionary session the record/playback
menu gives you the choice to continue recording, appending code to the
file. You must do this as the very first action after playback, after
the option will vanish from the menu. Brew must know the exact state
of everything when recording starts.

Please note, that the evolution may not use *anything* else (like
genomes, created other worlds or somesuch) than what was created
during the playback of the file in question. So you best restart brew,
play back the file and switch to recording, if you want to extend an
existing record file.




File: brew.info, Node: Record benchmark, Next: Playback, Prev: Record after playback, Up: Record and Playback

Recording to be used as a benchmark
-----------------------------------


Brew has some special features to make it comparatively easy to create
very complex benchmarks.

   * `Record benchmark'. Select this if you want to record an
     evolutionary session as benchmark.

   * `Please give record file name'. Same as for normal recording.

   * `Now you should select an individual and set it to a spot'. Same
     as for normal recording.

   * `Now go back to the main screen and set the individual'. Same as
     for normal recording.

   * Now you continue as usual, but you might spread some assert state
     entries at critical places to make sure the bench plays right.

   * `Finish benchmark'. Do *not* switch recording off the normal way
     when you are done, but select this entry instead.

        * `Saving code to assert current brew state to:
          brew-recorded.fs You can give a comment'. A final assert
          state entry is appended to the record file and you should
          give a very short comment that will be displayed together
          with the result of the state check.

        * `Shall I append code for benchmark start from command line?
          y/n'. This would append code to `maybe-run-benchmark.fs' to
          recognise the new bench. See source for more information.

        * `Give the benchmark name'. Please name your benchmark here.


Brew now gives you a short information about what it has done, like:

I'm appending the following line to maybe-run-benchmark.fs
[DEFINED] my-new-bench [IF]   include benchmarks/my-new-bench.fs      [THEN]

I copy the file to the benchmark directory:
benchmarks/my-new-bench.fs

After that you can execute the benchmark from the command line if the
Forth you use has an option to interpret a string on start up. It is
enough to `CREATE benchmark-name' as in `gforth -e "CREATE
my-new-bench" brew.fs' and brew will start the bench and terminate
when it's finished. So startup time (including brews compilation) is
*included* in the measured time. This is intentional.

Very likely you must edit the benchmark file by hand, i.e. you will
probably like to switch display off during the bench. Note that brew
has spread comments throughout the file that try to give you hints,
where you might want to edit something.




File: brew.info, Node: Playback, Prev: Record benchmark, Up: Record and Playback

Playback a recorded evolutionary programming session.
-----------------------------------------------------


Select `Playback' in the `Record and Playback menu'.

Choose a playback file.
(If you don't, the default record file name is probed).

That's it....


To interrupt playback just press a key. Brew will ask you if you want
to continue (`c') or quit (`q').




