Brews default directory tree
----------------------------

   * `brew/INPUTS/' Directory for input files (except configuration
     files). You can change it by defining `input-dir' as compile
     option.

        * `brew/INPUTS/genes/' Directory for genes (of the new
          gene/mutation version). Predefined relative to `INPUTS/'.

        * `brew/INPUTS/experiments/' Directory for experiments (*Note
          Experiments::), each one having it's own subdirectory, which
          are not listed here.

        * `brew/INPUTS/extensions/' Directory for optional extensions.

             * `brew/INPUTS/extensions/debugging/' Directory for
               optional debugging extensions. See the README files in
               the directory.

        * `brew/INPUTS/individuals/' Directory for individuals.


   * `brew/OUTPUT/' Directory for all output files. You can change it
     by defining `out-dir' as compile option.

        * `brew/OUTPUT/FORTH/' Directory for Forth code text files
          created by brew. Predefined relative to `OUTPUTS/'.

        * `brew/OUTPUT/rec-play/' Brew puts it's recorded files (as
          Forth source text files) here. Predefined relative to
          `OUTPUTS/'.

        * `brew/OUTPUT/log/' Brews log file directory. Predefined
          relative to `OUTPUTS/'.

        * `brew/OUTPUT/tmp/' Temporary brew files. Predefined relative
          to `OUTPUTS/'. Brew also puts some special output files here
          telling you that it has done so.


   * `brew/texi/' Main documentation directory.




File: brew.info, Node: Program files, Next: Genes files, Prev: Directory tree, Up: Files

Brew program source files
-------------------------

   * `brew.fs' Main program file.

   * `system-dependent.fs' Fork to load system dependent adaptions and
     definitions.

        * `gforth.fs' Adaptions to Gforth.

        * `pfe.fs' Adaptions to pfe.

        * `iForth.fs' Adaptions to iForth.

        * `bigFORTH.fs' BigForth adaptions.

   * `common-words.fs' Words commonly found in many Forth systems.
     Define them if they are not defined in the used Forth system.

   * `basics.fs' Some basic definitions I use in my programs.

   * `advanced.fs' Some basic definitions which can't be defined in
     `basics.fs' yet.

   * `brew-basics.fs' Some basic brew words. Defining them early
     avoids some dependency problems.

   * `allocation-pointers.fs' Deals with allocated memory blocks that
     will possibly get resized.

   * `block-variables.fs' Attempt to get faster variables in memory
     blocks. Depreciated.

   * `blockVARIABLEs-brew.fs' Brew variables defined as
     `block-variables'. Depreciated.

   * `dp-speed-align.fs' Trying influence of aligning dictionary
     pointer on speed.

   * `memory-speed-align.fs' Aligning chunks of memory for speed.

   * `random.fs' Random number generators.

   * `lists.fs' Linked lists, possibly having multiple data fields.

   * `listed-masks.fs' Masks to be written as text (i.e. as Forth
     source).

   * `string-lists.fs' Lists containing stringbuf handles for dynamic
     string storage.

   * `string-replace.fs' Building tables of fixed strings and using
     them to replace strings by other strings.

   * `association-lists.fs' Lists of keys and associated data.

   * `probability-lists.fs' Lists with relative probabilities to be
     selected randomly.

   * `sorted-lists.fs' Build a sorted copy of a list possibly having
     multiple data fields. Sorting is done numerically on one of the
     data fields. Very simple minded insertion sort implementation.

   * `stringbuf-0.4.fs' Memory buffers originally implemented to
     concatenate strings and the like. Used in brew for many different
     purposes.

   * `simple-stringbuf.fs' Simple (fixed size) buffers for strings and
     the like. Maybe obsolete, as the new ordinary stringbuf version
     is much faster then the old one was.

   * `console-codes.fs' Cursor and color management for the Linux text
     console.

   * `screen-size.fs' Screen size constants (defaults).

   * `display.fs' High level brew display interface.

   * `keybuf.fs' Simple key buffering.

   * `user-IO.fs' Advanced keyboard I/O words.

   * `key-mapping.fs' Maps special key events to menu key codes.

   * `mouse.fs' Faked mouse interface on top of an old implementation
     for Atari. Waiting to be reactivated on Linux console.

   * `menu.fs' User interface as active text menus.

   * `fileselect.fs' Experimental simple file interface.

   * `maybe-do.fs' User interface to do quite arbitrary things on nucs
     or spots that meet a certain condition. Quite hairy code...

   * `worlds.fs' Virtual world. New version allowing multiple multi
     dimensional worlds of arbitrary size.

   * `world-loop.fs' Looping over all spots of the virtual world.

   * `world-spots-arrayed.fs' Spots implemented as arrays.

   * `world-spots-localized.fs' Alternative spot implementation with
     the intention to speed up things by localising spot data for
     cache consistency. On my system it's actually slower.... The
     current brew versions do not fully support this world
     implementation any more, but it might get reactivated, when it
     would give speed advantage on future processor designs.

   * `symbols-stack.fs' The mutation process selects it's genes doing
     simple type checking of the stack data that the genes work with.
     The types are mapped to one char stack type symbols. In old brew
     versions I used the data stack to play with these symbols. This
     implementation uses strings internally, but still looks like a
     stack.

   * `genes-0.3.fs' Newer gene/mutation implementation.

   * `mutation-0.3.fs' Newer gene/mutation implementation.

   * `gene-edit.fs' User interface to examine genes and whole genomes
     and to edit them by hand.

   * `gene-alternatives.fs' Some genes like `drop' or `swap' have type
     variants for data types like integer values and addresses. While
     mutation always will select the right variant, the user will
     probably just write `drop' or `swap' when he edits a genome by
     hand. So brew must be able to figure out what exactly was meant.
 
   * `gene-pool.fs' Gene pools with relative probabilities to be used
     by mutation.

   * `statistics.fs' ASCII bar graphs of statistical data.

   * `reporting.fs' Writing very detailed log files.

   * `manual.fs' Show manual node corresponding to the context.

   * `dynamic-key-bindings.fs' Interpreting this file adds some key
     bindings in brews main screen if the words are defined.

   * `mixed-old-stuff.fs' Mixed relicts from very early brew
     development still used in some old demos, benchmarks and the
     like.

   * `INPUTS/individuals/old-brew-individuals.fs' Individuals left
     over from very old brew versions.

   * `old-demos.fs' Old style demos not guaranteed to work in this
     brew version any more.

   * `maybe-run-benchmark.fs' Fork to run benchmarks if a benchmark
     name is defined from command line.

   * `bcompat-11-12.fs' Downwards compatibility to run
     `transit-11-bench-A' and `transit-12-bench'.

   * `debuging.fs' Words to help debugging.

   * `faked-genes.fs' Faking some genes for interactive debugging.

   * `compile-switches.fs' Compile features, leave them out or compile
     them with a run time switch. New and not used yet.

   * `scan.fs' New scanning mechanism. Not used yet.




