File: brew.info, Node: Temporary files, Next: Informative files, Prev: Output files, Up: Files

Brews temporary files in `brew/OUTPUT/tmp/'.
--------------------------------------------

Brew creates some temporary files in its `tmp/' directory which
defaults to `brew/OUTPUT/tmp/'.

If you leave brew like intended (*Note Getting started::) it will
remove most of them, but there are some exceptions:

   * `brew-identity'. On startup brew will create a file
     `brew//OUTPUT/tmp/brew-identity', if it does not exist already.
     It contains a integer number which is increased by one each time
     a new brew gets started. Brew uses it to define a unique identity
     for each running brew, and will append the number to many file
     names, making it possible to run multiple brew incarnations at
     the same time, without getting confused by the others temporary
     files.

   * `created-files_nnn' (where `nnn' is the identity number) contains
     a list of output files created during this brew session. The list
     will be displayed on exit and the files will not be removed
     automatically, nor will be the list. Do this by hand when you're
     done with it.

   * `Special output files'. Some special output files will default to
     brews temporary directory too, while others (more important ones)
     like record or code files have their own default directory. As
     mentioned above, brew will inform you about the location of
     produced files and leave this information in `created-files_nnn'
     for later reference.

   * `tmp-files_nnn' (where `nnn' is the identity number) contains a
     list of temporary files that will be removed on exit, as the file
     itself will be.




File: brew.info, Node: Informative files, Next: Programming tool files, Prev: Temporary files, Up: Files

Documentation, versions, development, conventions....
-----------------------------------------------------

   * `texi/' Main documentation directory.

        * `texi/brew.texi' Source of this documentation in texinfo
          format.

        * `texi/brew.info' This documentation in info format.

        * `texi/brew.html' This documentation in HTML. Produce this
          file by saying `makeinfo --html brew.texi'.

